texts.text: Approved Package of Practice for Cotton in Karnataka State

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Cotton is a major commercial crop grown in almost all the Agro-climatic zones  of  Karnataka.  All  the  four  cultivated  species  of  cotton viz,.  Gossypium  arboreum, G. herbaceum, G.  barbadense, and G.  hirsutum are  grown  in  the  state  where  in Gossypium hirsutum has  the  major  share  of  the  hybrid  cotton  grown.  Area  under  cotton  during  the  year 2007-08, was 3.7 lakh hectares with a production and productivity of 6.0 lakh bales and 365 kg lint/ha respectively. Area under Bt cotton was to the extent of 0.8 lakh hectares during 2007-08.

texts.text: 2.1  Seed, seed treatment.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Use delinted seeds for uniform and higher germination. Adopt the following method for delinting of cotton seeds.
texts.text: Use delinted seeds for uniform and higher germination. Adopt the following method for delinting of cotton seeds.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Soak 1 kg of cotton seeds in 100 ml commercial grade Sulphuric acid (H2SO4) for ten minutes.
texts.text: Soak 1 kg of cotton seeds in 100 ml commercial grade Sulphuric acid (H2SO4) for ten minutes.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Wash the acid treated seeds with 2% Calcium Chloride (CaCl2), then with clean water and  dry  the  seeds  under  sunlight  and  use  for  sowing  after  recommended  seed treatment.
texts.text: Wash the acid treated seeds with 2% Calcium Chloride (CaCl2), then with clean water and  dry  the  seeds  under  sunlight  and  use  for  sowing  after  recommended  seed treatment.

texts.label: list_item

texts.text: Treat  the  seeds  required  for  one  hectare  area  with  500g  Azospirillum  and  500g Phosphorous Solubilising Bacteria (PSB) before  sowing which can save 20 kg N and 10 P2O5 /ha.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Treat the seeds with 10 g Imidacloprid 70WS or 5 g Thiomethaxam 70 WS to reduce the sucking pest incidence up to 35-40 days of sowing.

texts.label: list_item

texts.label: list_item

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Under assured rainfall conditions apply 50% N, entire dose of P2O5  and K2O as basal at the time of sowing  and top dress remaining 50% N at 60 DAS.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Under  irrigated conditions in Zone -3 apply  25 % N & K2O and  entire P2O5 as basal at sowing  and  top dress 50 % N & K2O in three equal splits at 50, 80 and 110 DAS.

texts.label: list_item

texts.label: list_item

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: 2.6. Post sowing operations and weed management
texts.text: 2.6. Post sowing operations and weed management

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Keep the plots weed free up to 60 days as the crop growth is slow during this period  and this  is the critical crop growth stage  for crop weed competition.
texts.text: Keep the plots weed free up to 60 days as the crop growth is slow during this period  and this  is the critical crop growth stage  for crop weed competition.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Three - four  intercultivations  at  an  interval  of  15  days  after  30  DAS  helps  in  controlling weeds and acts as dust mulch in conserving the available soil moisture.
texts.text: Three - four  intercultivations  at  an  interval  of  15  days  after  30  DAS  helps  in  controlling weeds and acts as dust mulch in conserving the available soil moisture.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · In rainfed situations weeds can be managed effectively by 2-3 intercultivations followed by hand weeding.
texts.text: In rainfed situations weeds can be managed effectively by 2-3 intercultivations followed by hand weeding.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · In  transitional  and  irrigated  areas  integrated  weed  management  proved  effective  in controlling  the  weeds.  Pre  emergent  application  of    Diuron  (80%)  @  1.25  kg/ha  or Pendimethalin (30 EC) @ 3 lit/ha in 500-750 lits of water, immediately after sowing (with sufficient soil moisture) coupled with one hand  weeding  and  intercultivation is recommended.

texts.orig: 2.10  Physiological disorders in cotton.
texts.text: 2.10  Physiological disorders in cotton.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Square drying, flowers and premature boll dropping and leaf reddening are the major Physiological disorders in cotton. These can be effectively managed and minimized by the following measures.
texts.text: Square drying, flowers and premature boll dropping and leaf reddening are the major Physiological disorders in cotton. These can be effectively managed and minimized by the following measures.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Squares, flowers and boll dropping can be minimized by foliar sprays of   Planofix @ 0.25ml/lit of water during pre flowering (55-60 DAS) and peak flowering stage ( 80-90 DAS) of the crop.
texts.text: Squares, flowers and boll dropping can be minimized by foliar sprays of   Planofix @ 0.25ml/lit of water during pre flowering (55-60 DAS) and peak flowering stage ( 80-90 DAS) of the crop.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: · Twice  foliar  sprays  of  1%  MgSO4  or  2%  urea  or  DAP  at  90  DAS  and  110  DAS reduces the leaf reddening during winter season.
texts.text: Twice  foliar  sprays  of  1%  MgSO4  or  2%  urea  or  DAP  at  90  DAS  and  110  DAS reduces the leaf reddening during winter season.
